// @check
// @error-at 10:7 Type `D` is defined in terms of itself with no base type, so it can never have a value
// A directly self-cyclic alias `type D = D` is degenerate NONSENSE — defined
// purely in terms of itself, no base case, so nothing can ever inhabit it. It
// gets an honest message that says so (PR #189 review), NOT the old misleading
// "opaque/recursive type aliases are not yet supported" (which implied a future
// feature). Exactly ONE error: the never-value diagnostic is scoped to a `never`
// produced by a CONCRETE empty intersection (tagged), so it does NOT fire a
// second, duplicate error on the self-cycle's bare `never`.
type D = D
let d: D = 0
